WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:06.880 --> 00:00:09.220
- Welcome to this
panel, which is called

00:00:09.220 --> 00:00:12.580
Ways of Knowing the City.

00:00:12.580 --> 00:00:14.890
And we have three speakers.

00:00:14.890 --> 00:00:17.320
I'll tell you a bit
about them in a moment.

00:00:17.320 --> 00:00:20.560
And we have a dynamic format,
which I'll also explain.

00:00:20.560 --> 00:00:24.130
But first, a little bit
about the topic, affect

00:00:24.130 --> 00:00:28.300
and experience and a rich
array of sensory information

00:00:28.300 --> 00:00:32.049
will always be essential
parts of knowing a city.

00:00:32.049 --> 00:00:35.740
Modern media and the city
are closely intertwined.

00:00:35.740 --> 00:00:39.070
Film is like the
kinetics of experience

00:00:39.070 --> 00:00:42.880
in the city with its new
forms of modern transport.

00:00:42.880 --> 00:00:47.950
Photography is like a glimpse,
a vignette, a framed moment.

00:00:47.950 --> 00:00:52.510
In the 19th century, French
poet Charles Baudelaire imagined

00:00:52.510 --> 00:00:55.330
the persona of a
[NON-ENGLISH SPEECH],

00:00:55.330 --> 00:00:58.510
a stroller, or someone who
walked the city in order

00:00:58.510 --> 00:01:03.220
to experience it and to take in
fleeting expressions and to be

00:01:03.220 --> 00:01:07.300
simultaneously part of
and apart from the crowd.

00:01:07.300 --> 00:01:10.760
And these observations would
be social and aesthetic.

00:01:10.760 --> 00:01:13.090
So Baudelaire's
[NON-ENGLISH SPEECH] has had

00:01:13.090 --> 00:01:17.350
a long after-life as a figure
for urban life and even

00:01:17.350 --> 00:01:19.180
for modernity itself.

00:01:19.180 --> 00:01:23.110
And the [NON-ENGLISH SPEECH]
anticipates street photography

00:01:23.110 --> 00:01:23.935
and even tourism.

00:01:26.650 --> 00:01:30.850
Cities function as keepers of
cultural and historical memory

00:01:30.850 --> 00:01:31.810
as well.

00:01:31.810 --> 00:01:34.780
Scholar Andreas
Huyssen posits cities

00:01:34.780 --> 00:01:40.000
as palimpsests of history,
incarnation of time in stone,

00:01:40.000 --> 00:01:44.350
sites of memory extending
both in time and space.

00:01:44.350 --> 00:01:48.280
And Italo Calvino, in
his novel from 1972,

00:01:48.280 --> 00:01:51.370
Invisible Cities
wrote that quote,

00:01:51.370 --> 00:01:53.680
"the city does
not tell its past,

00:01:53.680 --> 00:01:57.310
but contains it like the
lines of a hand written

00:01:57.310 --> 00:02:01.000
in the corners of the streets,
the gratings of the windows,

00:02:01.000 --> 00:02:05.480
the banisters of the steps, the
antennae of the lightning rods,

00:02:05.480 --> 00:02:08.380
the poles of the flags,
every segment marked

00:02:08.380 --> 00:02:13.390
in turn with scratches,
indentations, and scrolls."

00:02:13.390 --> 00:02:15.430
Our understanding
of city environments

00:02:15.430 --> 00:02:18.610
will always be intertwined with
the development of literature,

00:02:18.610 --> 00:02:23.570
film, photography, and newer
media as artistic modes.

00:02:23.570 --> 00:02:26.230
Today, in this
first panel, we will

00:02:26.230 --> 00:02:31.540
ask how we can connect these
nuanced humanistic perspectives

00:02:31.540 --> 00:02:34.000
and their document
of human experience

00:02:34.000 --> 00:02:36.910
with new forms of
media and big data that

00:02:36.910 --> 00:02:39.160
investigate the modern
urban experience

00:02:39.160 --> 00:02:41.560
and produce new
forms of knowledge

00:02:41.560 --> 00:02:45.400
using powerful new tools
and conceptual paradigms.

00:02:45.400 --> 00:02:47.620
How do the non-human
and the human

00:02:47.620 --> 00:02:50.590
intersect in urban
environments today?

00:02:50.590 --> 00:02:53.110
Collectively, we'll try
to make some headway

00:02:53.110 --> 00:02:55.700
on this topic in panel one.

00:02:55.700 --> 00:02:59.260
This panel lasts in total
for an hour and a half.

00:02:59.260 --> 00:03:02.500
First, we'll have presentations
about 15 minutes each

00:03:02.500 --> 00:03:05.770
from our three speakers who are
in the order in which they'll

00:03:05.770 --> 00:03:09.040
present, Heidi Ewing
who is a filmmaker

00:03:09.040 --> 00:03:13.270
and co-director of the Emmy
awarding film Detropia,

00:03:13.270 --> 00:03:15.700
a documentary about
the contemporary state

00:03:15.700 --> 00:03:19.840
of her hometown, Detroit,
which premiered at the Sundance

00:03:19.840 --> 00:03:21.880
festival in 2012.

00:03:21.880 --> 00:03:25.180
Mark Shepard, professor of
architecture and media studies

00:03:25.180 --> 00:03:29.380
from the University of Buffalo,
a practitioner and a theorist

00:03:29.380 --> 00:03:32.290
who explores in his
work the complex notion

00:03:32.290 --> 00:03:34.840
of the sentient city.

00:03:34.840 --> 00:03:37.270
We tend to think of
people as being sentient,

00:03:37.270 --> 00:03:39.580
but in fact cities can be.

00:03:39.580 --> 00:03:45.130
And finally, Sooni Taraporevela,
the photographer, screenwriter,

00:03:45.130 --> 00:03:46.390
and director.

00:03:46.390 --> 00:03:49.450
And her photography
exhibition Home

00:03:49.450 --> 00:03:54.790
in the City, Bombay
1976 to Mumbai 2016

00:03:54.790 --> 00:03:57.070
is currently showing at
the Whitworth Gallery

00:03:57.070 --> 00:03:59.200
in Manchester,
England and has been

00:03:59.200 --> 00:04:02.230
listed as one of the top five
art exhibitions in the United

00:04:02.230 --> 00:04:04.450
Kingdom by The Guardian.

00:04:04.450 --> 00:04:08.170
So after the panelists have
completed their presentations,

00:04:08.170 --> 00:04:10.510
I will moderate a short
discussion among them

00:04:10.510 --> 00:04:12.190
for about 15 minutes.

00:04:12.190 --> 00:04:14.710
And then we'll
have a Q&amp;A session

00:04:14.710 --> 00:04:16.480
where members of
the audience can

00:04:16.480 --> 00:04:19.060
come to the mic that will
be in the central aisle

00:04:19.060 --> 00:04:21.890
and ask questions of the
presenters themselves.

00:04:21.890 --> 00:04:25.840
So with no further ado, I
suggest that we get started.

00:04:25.840 --> 00:04:28.030
And I invite Heidi
Ewing to the podium

00:04:28.030 --> 00:04:29.420
to give her presentation.

00:04:29.420 --> 00:04:30.279
Thank you.

00:04:30.279 --> 00:04:31.686
[APPLAUSE]

00:04:31.686 --> 00:04:33.093
- Thank you very much.

00:04:35.907 --> 00:04:38.130
Well, thank you to
Liz, and to Radcliffe,

00:04:38.130 --> 00:04:40.020
and everyone here for
taking an interest

00:04:40.020 --> 00:04:42.270
in cities and urbanism.

00:04:42.270 --> 00:04:44.160
I think it's funny
that Angela mentioned

00:04:44.160 --> 00:04:46.950
the need for confessions
when we talk about cities.

00:04:46.950 --> 00:04:49.080
It's very true about Detroit.

00:04:49.080 --> 00:04:52.830
So my confession, I actually
grew up 20 minutes north

00:04:52.830 --> 00:04:54.470
of Detroit.

00:04:54.470 --> 00:04:55.800
It's very important.

00:04:55.800 --> 00:04:59.490
And my father was a Detroiter.

00:04:59.490 --> 00:05:03.060
And my parents were part of
the so-called white flight out

00:05:03.060 --> 00:05:06.330
of Detroit after the
uprisings, riots,

00:05:06.330 --> 00:05:09.520
however you'd like
to call it, in 1967.

00:05:09.520 --> 00:05:11.880
My granny, from the
north side of Detroit,

00:05:11.880 --> 00:05:13.980
refused to leave till
she couldn't get up

00:05:13.980 --> 00:05:15.390
her stairs at the end.

00:05:15.390 --> 00:05:17.250
Her body gave out.

00:05:17.250 --> 00:05:20.250
She used to proudly call
herself the last white lady

00:05:20.250 --> 00:05:22.110
on the block.

00:05:22.110 --> 00:05:23.970
That's my confession.

00:05:23.970 --> 00:05:27.660
So has a documentary director,
I make a living following

00:05:27.660 --> 00:05:30.300
the stories of real people
and, with my camera,

00:05:30.300 --> 00:05:33.519
capturing the change.

00:05:33.519 --> 00:05:35.310
And, well, you hope
there's going to change

00:05:35.310 --> 00:05:38.710
and evolutions over
a period of time.

00:05:38.710 --> 00:05:40.740
And what I've learned
in my career so far

00:05:40.740 --> 00:05:43.410
is that narratives are
very, very powerful.

00:05:43.410 --> 00:05:45.750
A narrative is a powerful tool.

00:05:45.750 --> 00:05:48.940
In the film Detropia, which
is one of my films from 2012,

00:05:48.940 --> 00:05:50.790
I had the chance to
chronicle the narrative

00:05:50.790 --> 00:05:52.890
of an entire place or
attempt to chronicle

00:05:52.890 --> 00:05:54.780
the narrative of an
entire place, which

00:05:54.780 --> 00:05:56.545
would be the city of Detroit.

00:05:56.545 --> 00:05:58.170
And during the
production of this film,

00:05:58.170 --> 00:06:00.090
something unexpected happened.

00:06:00.090 --> 00:06:03.660
Before my eyes, the
conversation about Detroit

00:06:03.660 --> 00:06:05.070
completely changed.

00:06:05.070 --> 00:06:08.100
From the time I began
shooting the film in 2009

00:06:08.100 --> 00:06:11.220
to its theatrical
release in 2012,

00:06:11.220 --> 00:06:14.850
the local narrative,
meaning the story

00:06:14.850 --> 00:06:18.760
that the Detroit residents
themselves told themselves

00:06:18.760 --> 00:06:23.150
about their city, began to clash
with the national narrative,

00:06:23.150 --> 00:06:26.620
which by that I mean the way in
which outsiders and the media

00:06:26.620 --> 00:06:28.960
chose to see the city.

00:06:28.960 --> 00:06:31.620
And this sort of happened,
I guess, by coincidence

00:06:31.620 --> 00:06:33.790
while we were making the film.

00:06:33.790 --> 00:06:36.460
So I'd like to start with
the Time Magazine cover.

00:06:36.460 --> 00:06:39.010
So this was 2009.

00:06:39.010 --> 00:06:41.440
This was when I
began to Detropia.

00:06:41.440 --> 00:06:44.530
Soon after this, Time Magazine
published the cover story,

00:06:44.530 --> 00:06:46.420
"The Tragedy of Detroit."

00:06:46.420 --> 00:06:48.610
The article described
Detroit as a place that

00:06:48.610 --> 00:06:52.510
looked as if it had quote,
"been savaged by a hurricane

00:06:52.510 --> 00:06:56.050
or submerged by a
ravenous flood," unquote.

00:06:56.050 --> 00:07:00.070
Why hadn't the world
noticed, the article asked.

00:07:00.070 --> 00:07:03.110
To me, who grew up in
the Detroit Metro area,

00:07:03.110 --> 00:07:05.290
Time was simply
mimicking what we

00:07:05.290 --> 00:07:08.590
had been shouting for years,
what we knew all along.

00:07:08.590 --> 00:07:12.850
Segregation, racial
inequality, subpar education,

00:07:12.850 --> 00:07:18.130
massive governmental corruption
at the local level, an auto

00:07:18.130 --> 00:07:23.860
industry that had refused to
change, a city that refused

00:07:23.860 --> 00:07:27.910
to diversify, crime was
wild, jobs had vanished,

00:07:27.910 --> 00:07:29.440
we knew these things already.

00:07:29.440 --> 00:07:32.350
The article was not a shock.

00:07:32.350 --> 00:07:35.350
But the nation seemed shocked
as this got a lot of attention.

00:07:35.350 --> 00:07:39.860
This Time Magazine cover, there
was a lot of recoverage on it.

00:07:39.860 --> 00:07:42.550
But the interesting
thing is we locals,

00:07:42.550 --> 00:07:44.710
we Detroiters and
Metro Detroiters--

00:07:44.710 --> 00:07:48.220
my father was in manufacturing,
so was very close

00:07:48.220 --> 00:07:50.500
to our hearts, what was
happening to Detroit--

00:07:50.500 --> 00:07:53.650
we had another narrative, a
counter-narrative perhaps,

00:07:53.650 --> 00:07:55.810
that we told about our own city.

00:07:55.810 --> 00:07:58.220
And that was one very
close to our hearts.

00:07:58.220 --> 00:08:02.020
And it was a story of deep pride
in Detroit's place in history.

00:08:02.020 --> 00:08:04.330
To us, in symbolic
terms at the very least,

00:08:04.330 --> 00:08:08.170
Detroit was the most
important place in America.

00:08:08.170 --> 00:08:10.750
And when I started
shooting Detropia,

00:08:10.750 --> 00:08:13.750
I found that that
narrative was still alive.

00:08:13.750 --> 00:08:16.540
And so I'd like to show
you a clip from the film.

00:08:16.540 --> 00:08:18.970
This is one of my
subjects, George McGregor,

00:08:18.970 --> 00:08:23.114
President of United
Auto Workers Local 22.

00:08:23.114 --> 00:08:23.780
