00:08:38.140 --> 00:08:40.390
they turned that from
an automobile factory

00:08:40.390 --> 00:08:43.760
to building airplanes
right there on 4th Street.

00:08:43.760 --> 00:08:44.810
We built everything.

00:08:44.810 --> 00:08:46.600
We put them on a
ship and shipped them

00:08:46.600 --> 00:08:48.812
to England and everywhere.

00:08:48.812 --> 00:08:49.770
Y'all know what we did.

00:08:49.770 --> 00:08:51.970
Keep up with that history.

00:08:51.970 --> 00:08:54.100
Now, we can't even
buy American made

00:08:54.100 --> 00:08:56.575
washing machine or an iron.

00:09:00.281 --> 00:09:04.090
So where did our
manufacturing base go?

00:09:04.090 --> 00:09:05.410
Where did it all go?

00:09:05.410 --> 00:09:06.880
Because we built everything.

00:09:06.880 --> 00:09:14.520
We built everything,
everything, America did.

00:09:14.520 --> 00:09:16.890
We have a standard
of living in America

00:09:16.890 --> 00:09:20.650
that the working guy provided
a standard of living,

00:09:20.650 --> 00:09:21.900
which is eroding now.

00:09:21.900 --> 00:09:25.770
But it's a standard of
living that the working guy,

00:09:25.770 --> 00:09:29.750
and it started right
here in Detroit.

00:09:29.750 --> 00:09:33.890
Right here in Detroit, a middle
class started right here.

00:09:33.890 --> 00:09:35.260
Everybody knows.

00:09:35.260 --> 00:09:37.880
We just got to face
up to it, so we're

00:09:37.880 --> 00:09:39.550
able to send our kids to school.

00:09:39.550 --> 00:09:41.426
We're able to set up
a little bit of money.

00:09:41.426 --> 00:09:42.800
Some of our guys
were able enough

00:09:42.800 --> 00:09:44.820
to get a little place
of north or whatever.

00:09:44.820 --> 00:09:49.185
It's middle class, got a boat.

00:09:49.185 --> 00:09:50.720
You understand what I'm saying?

00:09:50.720 --> 00:09:52.639
Middle class.

00:09:52.639 --> 00:09:53.180
Middle class.

00:09:56.110 --> 00:10:03.700
Leave it to Beaver, the white
house, the picket fence.

00:10:03.700 --> 00:10:06.656
Leave it to Beaver, wasn't
that the middle class?

00:10:06.656 --> 00:10:08.230
Come on now.

00:10:08.230 --> 00:10:09.970
We're looking at
it on TV, right?

00:10:09.970 --> 00:10:11.570
Weren't we?

00:10:11.570 --> 00:10:15.180
Do Then we see it
come into our lives.

00:10:15.180 --> 00:10:16.780
There it is, the middle class.

00:10:19.576 --> 00:10:20.510
[END VIDEO PLAYBACK]

00:10:20.510 --> 00:10:25.130
- I love that guy,
George McGregor.

00:10:25.130 --> 00:10:28.424
What a way to synthesize the
feelings that a lot of us

00:10:28.424 --> 00:10:29.840
have and a lot of
Detroiters still

00:10:29.840 --> 00:10:32.750
have about the place and
the importance of Detroit.

00:10:32.750 --> 00:10:35.869
You know, hearkening
back to Angela's talk,

00:10:35.869 --> 00:10:37.910
you know, he is a product
of the great migration.

00:10:37.910 --> 00:10:40.190
His family was from
the south and came up

00:10:40.190 --> 00:10:43.310
to work in the
factories, he included.

00:10:43.310 --> 00:10:49.022
And the black middle
class, he's evidence of it.

00:10:49.022 --> 00:10:50.480
Anyway, my parents
and grandparents

00:10:50.480 --> 00:10:51.551
all sounded like George.

00:10:51.551 --> 00:10:54.050
Detroit's role in the creation
of the middle class lifestyle

00:10:54.050 --> 00:10:56.330
should be honored and cherished.

00:10:56.330 --> 00:10:59.900
This narrative acted as a type
of urban institutional memory

00:10:59.900 --> 00:11:02.180
shared by natives of the city.

00:11:02.180 --> 00:11:04.580
But what I found most
surprising while making Detropia

00:11:04.580 --> 00:11:08.960
is that this strong connection
to history, which we don't find

00:11:08.960 --> 00:11:11.529
that very often in
20-somethings right now,

00:11:11.529 --> 00:11:13.070
but this strong
connection to history

00:11:13.070 --> 00:11:15.860
was still prevalent even
among the youngest Detroiters

00:11:15.860 --> 00:11:18.170
I met who had never
experienced not

00:11:18.170 --> 00:11:21.170
even a moment of this heyday
that we always, always heard

00:11:21.170 --> 00:11:22.520
about.

00:11:22.520 --> 00:11:25.790
Even for them, Detroit
remained thick with nostalgia

00:11:25.790 --> 00:11:27.710
for the elusive past.

00:11:27.710 --> 00:11:33.530
And I'd never seen people
in their 20s feel so old

00:11:33.530 --> 00:11:39.140
and talk so old and have such a
grasp and nostalgia for an era

00:11:39.140 --> 00:11:40.400
that they never lived.

00:11:40.400 --> 00:11:43.160
And that I found over and
over while making Detropia.

00:11:43.160 --> 00:11:46.640
And that brings us to
Crystal and how she

00:11:46.640 --> 00:11:48.530
interacted with her own city.

00:11:48.530 --> 00:11:50.450
She was in her mid
20s when we met her.

00:11:50.450 --> 00:11:52.130
She was born and
raised in Detroit.

00:11:52.130 --> 00:11:55.670
She was one of the residents
that could easily have left,

00:11:55.670 --> 00:11:56.780
but had chosen to stay.

00:11:56.780 --> 00:11:58.820
And all the characters
in the film Detropia

00:11:58.820 --> 00:12:01.760
could have left, that we
focus on, and chose to stay.

00:12:01.760 --> 00:12:03.590
And that's very significant.

00:12:03.590 --> 00:12:05.810
But the city had too
much of a grip on her.

00:12:05.810 --> 00:12:10.370
And the past had too much of a
grip on her for her to leave.

00:12:10.370 --> 00:12:12.740
And she used to go when
she wasn't waiting tables,

00:12:12.740 --> 00:12:14.840
she would do urban explorations.

00:12:14.840 --> 00:12:17.030
And she would break
into old buildings

00:12:17.030 --> 00:12:19.180
and try to figure
out who lived there

00:12:19.180 --> 00:12:20.780
and what life had been like.

00:12:20.780 --> 00:12:25.652
So I'd like to show Crystal
