00:14:31.300 --> 00:14:35.920
the world, because I can damn
near see it from right here.

00:14:35.920 --> 00:14:37.305
Motown right up the street.

00:14:42.360 --> 00:14:44.240
We can't leave, man,
can't fucking leave.

00:14:54.960 --> 00:14:58.020
I feel like I was maybe
here a little while back,

00:14:58.020 --> 00:15:00.390
or I'm older than I
really am, but I just

00:15:00.390 --> 00:15:05.920
have this young body
and spirit and mind.

00:15:05.920 --> 00:15:10.110
But I have the memory of this
place when it was banging.

00:15:10.110 --> 00:15:13.270
That's how I feel.

00:15:13.270 --> 00:15:14.630
[END VIDEO PLAYBACK]

00:15:14.630 --> 00:15:16.520
So So I found people
like Crystal over

00:15:16.520 --> 00:15:18.410
and over again while
making Detropia

00:15:18.410 --> 00:15:21.590
that were haunted by
the past, something

00:15:21.590 --> 00:15:24.150
I didn't expect to find
when making the film.

00:15:24.150 --> 00:15:26.000
Crystal had every
reason to believe

00:15:26.000 --> 00:15:28.022
that she was the last
person on Earth that

00:15:28.022 --> 00:15:30.230
was interested in all these
empty blocks of her city,

00:15:30.230 --> 00:15:32.420
but that assumption
was very wrong.

00:15:32.420 --> 00:15:34.280
As we know, the
2008 market crash

00:15:34.280 --> 00:15:36.080
landed plenty of
young college grads

00:15:36.080 --> 00:15:38.090
back in their parents
basements, maybe

00:15:38.090 --> 00:15:39.870
in some of your basements.

00:15:39.870 --> 00:15:40.370
But

00:15:40.370 --> 00:15:44.000
Rumors of $500 houses,
large lofts for artists,

00:15:44.000 --> 00:15:47.300
and quasi-lawless city
in search of residents

00:15:47.300 --> 00:15:49.850
sounded pretty appealing
to some people.

00:15:49.850 --> 00:15:52.550
The newcomers, who are mostly
young single and white,

00:15:52.550 --> 00:15:54.800
came with no malice to Detroit.

00:15:54.800 --> 00:15:58.100
Yet, they also came with
little to no appreciation

00:15:58.100 --> 00:16:00.300
or understanding
of Detroit's past,

00:16:00.300 --> 00:16:03.350
including its very
charged racial past.

00:16:03.350 --> 00:16:05.840
They preferred to talk
about the new trendy ideas

00:16:05.840 --> 00:16:08.900
like large scale urban farming,
which was a major idea being

00:16:08.900 --> 00:16:11.420
floated in Detroit or
to start microbreweries

00:16:11.420 --> 00:16:12.849
or graphic design firms.

00:16:12.849 --> 00:16:14.390
They were not
interested in pondering

00:16:14.390 --> 00:16:16.190
all that had been lost before.

00:16:16.190 --> 00:16:19.430
They were not haunted
by the past of Detroit.

00:16:19.430 --> 00:16:22.130
Detroit gained 14,000
white residents

00:16:22.130 --> 00:16:24.290
between 2010 and 2014.

00:16:24.290 --> 00:16:27.410
It was the first uptick
like that in 60 years.

00:16:27.410 --> 00:16:29.970
This attitude that
a lot of them had,

00:16:29.970 --> 00:16:33.780
which was that Detroit was a
blank slate or an empty canvas,

00:16:33.780 --> 00:16:35.450
this idea crept in.

00:16:35.450 --> 00:16:37.070
Detroit was almost
their Petri dish

00:16:37.070 --> 00:16:40.424
for experimentation
of all kinds.

00:16:40.424 --> 00:16:41.840
The new narrative
was that Detroit

00:16:41.840 --> 00:16:44.990
could be almost a
playground for young whites.

00:16:44.990 --> 00:16:47.000
And they could live
cheaply and well.

00:16:47.000 --> 00:16:48.340
And here's an example of that.

00:16:48.340 --> 00:16:49.714
These are two
artists that we met

00:16:49.714 --> 00:16:53.120
that are in the film Detropia,
Steve and Dorota Coy.

00:16:53.120 --> 00:16:56.290
This is sort of just after they
moved into the city, the Coy's

00:16:56.290 --> 00:16:57.150
Detropia, please.

00:17:15.030 --> 00:17:17.619
- Dorota and I met in Hawaii.

00:17:17.619 --> 00:17:19.410
We knew we weren't
going to stay in Hawaii.

00:17:19.410 --> 00:17:21.490
And so we were just
tossing around places.

00:17:21.490 --> 00:17:24.347
We wanted to be somewhere
urban, of course.

00:17:24.347 --> 00:17:25.930
We had a project
that we wanted to do,

00:17:25.930 --> 00:17:28.780
like street art,
public installation.

00:17:28.780 --> 00:17:30.350
And so we just
started evaluating.

00:17:30.350 --> 00:17:32.170
We looked at Baltimore.

00:17:32.170 --> 00:17:34.150
We were looking
into New York City.

00:17:34.150 --> 00:17:37.410
And Detroit came up.

00:17:37.410 --> 00:17:39.430
And I knew that's
one thing Detroit

00:17:39.430 --> 00:17:43.380
had an abundance of was
space and old warehouses.

00:17:51.188 --> 00:17:54.860
I feel like we've assimilated
into that community of artists

00:17:54.860 --> 00:17:56.540
that are moving here
and coming here.

00:18:04.567 --> 00:18:05.400
That's pretty sweet.

00:18:18.330 --> 00:18:19.910
I've never had
appliances this nice,

00:18:19.910 --> 00:18:21.890
so I feel like I should
be taking care of them.

00:18:27.220 --> 00:18:27.720
Yeah.

00:18:27.720 --> 00:18:29.770
We bought just a
couple of weeks ago.

00:18:29.770 --> 00:18:33.380
And we're able to keep our
studio, because everything

00:18:33.380 --> 00:18:35.270
is so affordable.

00:18:39.760 --> 00:18:44.670
Detroit is constantly
amazing me.

00:18:44.670 --> 00:18:49.800
I feel like it's redefining
what the value of things are.

00:18:49.800 --> 00:18:53.699
You know, $25,000
for an amazing loft?

00:18:53.699 --> 00:18:54.240
I don't know.

00:18:54.240 --> 00:18:56.240
That just makes it
accessible to people like me.

00:18:56.240 --> 00:18:59.550
I would never be able to afford
to own a home as an artist.

00:18:59.550 --> 00:19:04.470
And here I am with a
studio and an apartment

00:19:04.470 --> 00:19:09.290
in a major city functioning
for like $700 or less a month.

00:19:14.250 --> 00:19:16.620
We can experiment here.

00:19:16.620 --> 00:19:21.103
Because if we fail, we haven't
really fallen anywhere.

00:19:25.287 --> 00:19:27.120
- So you see the
difference in the newcomers

00:19:27.120 --> 00:19:28.290
and the old timers there.

00:19:31.800 --> 00:19:34.200
You know, at first,
Detroiters reacted

00:19:34.200 --> 00:19:37.440
with curiosity and
skepticism at the newcomers

00:19:37.440 --> 00:19:41.130
and their embrace of this new
Detroit that they could see.

00:19:41.130 --> 00:19:42.930
And there was some
humorous headlines.

00:19:42.930 --> 00:19:44.970
My favorite headline was
from the Detroit Metro

00:19:44.970 --> 00:19:47.520
Times that was reacting
to these carpetbaggers.

00:19:47.520 --> 00:19:50.970
And it said, "Major Cities
Unloading Undesirable Hipsters

00:19:50.970 --> 00:19:53.360
in Detroit."

00:19:53.360 --> 00:19:56.630
Can I see the billboard
Bushwick, please?

00:19:56.630 --> 00:19:59.840
And you know, this was sort
of a little advertising.

00:19:59.840 --> 00:20:02.250
This is in Bushwick,
New York in Brooklyn.

00:20:02.250 --> 00:20:04.187
It's like, you're
going to be a hipster

00:20:04.187 --> 00:20:05.270
and have a hipster's life?

00:20:05.270 --> 00:20:07.640
You can live cheaper and
better if you come to Detroit.

00:20:07.640 --> 00:20:10.320
There was also this graffiti
campaign "move to Detroit,"

00:20:10.320 --> 00:20:12.160
which you would
see on the bridges.

00:20:12.160 --> 00:20:13.520
This was not a massive campaign.

00:20:13.520 --> 00:20:16.550
But it goes to show sort
of this looking at Detroit

00:20:16.550 --> 00:20:18.710
in a completely different way.

00:20:18.710 --> 00:20:21.350
And suddenly, it sort
of had a street cred.

00:20:21.350 --> 00:20:23.770
A lot of New York Times
articles and the like

00:20:23.770 --> 00:20:27.160
were obsessed with these
young white newcomers,

00:20:27.160 --> 00:20:30.099
endless articles about them.

00:20:30.099 --> 00:20:31.390
And what were they doing there?

00:20:31.390 --> 00:20:33.020
And would they
help save the city,

00:20:33.020 --> 00:20:34.670
and all of that sort of thing.

00:20:34.670 --> 00:20:36.260
So there's this
comeback narrative

00:20:36.260 --> 00:20:38.810
of Detroit started to arise.

00:20:38.810 --> 00:20:44.510
And it's really interesting,
because the corporations really

00:20:44.510 --> 00:20:46.510
soon followed all
of this coverage.

00:20:46.510 --> 00:20:50.020
In 2011, just as Detroit
entered bankruptcy proceedings,

00:20:50.020 --> 00:20:52.430
Shinola, the fancy
watch and bike company,

00:20:52.430 --> 00:20:54.000
set up shop in the city.

00:20:54.000 --> 00:20:56.870
Their pitch was that
by purchasing a $550

00:20:56.870 --> 00:20:59.840
watch or a $3,000
bicycle, hip consumers

00:20:59.840 --> 00:21:03.530
could buy into the revival
of one of America's

00:21:03.530 --> 00:21:05.240
great industrial cities.

00:21:05.240 --> 00:21:07.430
So corporations and investors
really heard the call.

00:21:07.430 --> 00:21:09.971
Dan Gilbert, the owner of the
Cleveland Cavaliers and Quicken

00:21:09.971 --> 00:21:12.530
Loans, began to scoop up a
lot of these skyscrapers that

00:21:12.530 --> 00:21:15.440
had been long emptied and
filled them with luxury lofts.

00:21:15.440 --> 00:21:17.960
In 2013, Whole
Foods came to town

00:21:17.960 --> 00:21:23.115
and was greeted with
a full-fledged frenzy.

00:21:23.115 --> 00:21:23.990
The city had arrived.

00:21:23.990 --> 00:21:26.030
Whole Foods was there.

00:21:26.030 --> 00:21:28.370
So the rebranding of
Detroit's national narrative

00:21:28.370 --> 00:21:30.200
had been sort of complete.

00:21:30.200 --> 00:21:33.800
But had the city actually
improve, and for whom?

00:21:33.800 --> 00:21:36.770
And who does this
revitalization benefit?

00:21:36.770 --> 00:21:39.770
Well, here are the facts,
just facts, just numbers.

00:21:39.770 --> 00:21:41.510
Detroit has been
number one on Forbes

00:21:41.510 --> 00:21:44.330
most dangerous cities list
now for four years in a row.

00:21:44.330 --> 00:21:47.930
Detroit only has enough
jobs to employ roughly 37%

00:21:47.930 --> 00:21:49.250
of the population.

00:21:49.250 --> 00:21:51.530
The public school
remains in a disgrace.

00:21:51.530 --> 00:21:53.060
On the whole, black
residents which

00:21:53.060 --> 00:21:54.980
make up over 80% of
the city have not

00:21:54.980 --> 00:21:57.260
benefited from this new Detroit.

00:21:57.260 --> 00:22:00.470
A very small area called
midtown in the downtown area,

00:22:00.470 --> 00:22:02.120
you see restaurants,
you see galleries,

00:22:02.120 --> 00:22:03.320
you see more tourists.

00:22:03.320 --> 00:22:05.630
You do see an economy
coming through here.

00:22:05.630 --> 00:22:07.760
But the rest of the
140 square miles

00:22:07.760 --> 00:22:11.000
remains exactly as I've
always remembered it

00:22:11.000 --> 00:22:12.860
since I was a child.

00:22:12.860 --> 00:22:15.770
Detroit declared
bankruptcy in 2013.

00:22:15.770 --> 00:22:18.960
Today, still the population
continues to decline.

00:22:18.960 --> 00:22:22.330
However, they think that
by 2018 the population,

00:22:22.330 --> 00:22:25.130
the endless decline,
might actually bottom out.

00:22:25.130 --> 00:22:26.940
And that is significant.

00:22:26.940 --> 00:22:29.960
It's not insignificant.

00:22:29.960 --> 00:22:31.127
But narratives are powerful.

00:22:31.127 --> 00:22:32.543
When I started to
Detropia, people

00:22:32.543 --> 00:22:34.340
would ask what I was
working on, I'd say,

00:22:34.340 --> 00:22:36.500
I'm spending a lot
of time in Detroit.

00:22:36.500 --> 00:22:39.820
And they would always answer,
I'm sorry to hear that.

00:22:39.820 --> 00:22:42.514
A snide remark, oh, Detroilet
and things like that.

00:22:42.514 --> 00:22:44.930
Now, when I say I'm going back
to Detroit for the weekend,

00:22:44.930 --> 00:22:46.220
they say, oh, my god, cool.

00:22:46.220 --> 00:22:47.750
I heard it's back now.

00:22:47.750 --> 00:22:50.140
And I'm dying to
go check it out.

00:22:50.140 --> 00:22:52.640
And maybe that narrative,
the Detroit phoenix

00:22:52.640 --> 00:22:56.030
rising from the ashes, will
someday become a reality.

00:22:56.030 --> 00:22:58.340
Perhaps, Detroit's
affordability and strange allure

00:22:58.340 --> 00:23:00.950
will continue to bring more
people to the city, people

00:23:00.950 --> 00:23:03.620
like yourselves, with
good ideas of how

00:23:03.620 --> 00:23:05.510
a greater number of
Detroiters can actually

00:23:05.510 --> 00:23:08.870
benefit from this new interest
and investment in the city.

00:23:08.870 --> 00:23:11.240
We're far off from this, I feel.

00:23:11.240 --> 00:23:14.120
But the fascination with
Detroit continues to grow.

00:23:14.120 --> 00:23:16.310
And somehow the city
has a hold on us.

00:23:16.310 --> 00:23:17.780
In fact, writer
Drew Philips likes

00:23:17.780 --> 00:23:20.600
to say Detroit is the most
interesting city on the planet.

00:23:20.600 --> 00:23:22.460
Because when you
scratch the surface,

00:23:22.460 --> 00:23:24.380
you only find a mirror.

00:23:24.380 --> 00:23:27.620
There's just something about
this city, about this story,

00:23:27.620 --> 00:23:28.960
we cannot shake.

00:23:28.960 --> 00:23:31.460
So I hope you continue
to explore it.

00:23:31.460 --> 00:23:33.530
Thank you so much for having me.

00:23:33.530 --> 00:23:42.650
[APPLAUSE]

00:23:42.650 --> 00:23:46.280
- So thank you first, of
course, to the organizers,

00:23:46.280 --> 00:23:52.630
to Eve, to Julie, to Erik,
and naturally to Dean Cohen

00:23:52.630 --> 00:23:54.550
supporting for
consistently supporting

00:23:54.550 --> 00:23:57.880
what seems to have been
an incredible run here

00:23:57.880 --> 00:23:59.890
in the Radcliffe Institute.

00:23:59.890 --> 00:24:03.610
I'd like to especially
thank you Eve Blau, who

00:24:03.610 --> 00:24:05.680
was the protagonist
in bringing me here

00:24:05.680 --> 00:24:09.640
last year to this workshop
on urban intermedia, which

00:24:09.640 --> 00:24:11.650
provided an impetus
for me to organize

00:24:11.650 --> 00:24:16.210
my thoughts around this issue of
how what we know about the city

00:24:16.210 --> 00:24:20.130
is conditioned through the
lens with which we see it

00:24:20.130 --> 00:24:25.550
and, subsequently, how that
lens in turn conditions us.

00:24:25.550 --> 00:24:26.050
You

00:24:26.050 --> 00:24:31.540
It's fortuitous to follow
Heidi, I think, in the sense

00:24:31.540 --> 00:24:35.650
that what I'm going to
talk about is in a sense

00:24:35.650 --> 00:24:39.490
the other side of what
might be described

00:24:39.490 --> 00:24:44.830
as the power of personal
narrative to articulate a place

00:24:44.830 --> 00:24:48.370
and how we read a
city through people.

00:24:48.370 --> 00:24:52.000
And I think we, in
the keynote, heard

00:24:52.000 --> 00:24:55.720
quite a bit about this
notion that people

00:24:55.720 --> 00:25:00.069
define cities, which then
in turn define people.

00:25:00.069 --> 00:25:02.110
So it's this relationship
that I'm interested in.

00:25:02.110 --> 00:25:04.780
And I'm interested
in looking forward

00:25:04.780 --> 00:25:11.170
in terms of contemporary
modes of observing

00:25:11.170 --> 00:25:15.100
the city, in particular the
role of big data, algorithms,

00:25:15.100 --> 00:25:18.670
and so-called intelligent
urban infrastructure

00:25:18.670 --> 00:25:21.220
are shaping what we know
about the city today

00:25:21.220 --> 00:25:24.730
and how, in turn, it's
beginning to shape us.

00:25:24.730 --> 00:25:27.130
And my interest here
lies in questioning

00:25:27.130 --> 00:25:30.340
how this reciprocal relationship
between the methods and objects

00:25:30.340 --> 00:25:34.300
of urban research changes
when we shift from employing

00:25:34.300 --> 00:25:37.750
representational tools by
which the present city is

00:25:37.750 --> 00:25:41.410
observed to methods involving
data mining and analysis that

00:25:41.410 --> 00:25:44.650
aim to derive observations
and make predictions

00:25:44.650 --> 00:25:47.950
about future situations.

00:25:47.950 --> 00:25:50.690
So this is primarily a
story about shifting focus

00:25:50.690 --> 00:25:53.650
from deploying representational
tools, such as the film

00:25:53.650 --> 00:25:56.880
camera as instruments
for recording

00:25:56.880 --> 00:26:01.660
or for urban observation,
to instrumenting

00:26:01.660 --> 00:26:04.150
physical environments
themselves,

00:26:04.150 --> 00:26:07.030
and ultimately the people
that inhabit them with sensors

00:26:07.030 --> 00:26:11.440
and software systems to quantify
urban life in ways that claim

00:26:11.440 --> 00:26:15.460
to lead to ever more
optimized, efficient,

00:26:15.460 --> 00:26:18.760
and sustainable cities.

00:26:18.760 --> 00:26:21.040
Now, devices for
observing the world

00:26:21.040 --> 00:26:22.870
have been around for a while.

00:26:22.870 --> 00:26:25.120
Much has been said about
the camera obscura,

00:26:25.120 --> 00:26:28.570
for instance, and its role
in recording geometrically

00:26:28.570 --> 00:26:30.700
accurate views of the city.

00:26:30.700 --> 00:26:33.430
These are four drawings
by Canaletto representing

00:26:33.430 --> 00:26:37.360
the Campa San Giovanni e
Paolo in Venice, produced

00:26:37.360 --> 00:26:41.080
with the aid of a
camera obscura resulting

00:26:41.080 --> 00:26:43.510
in studies for this painting.

00:26:43.510 --> 00:26:46.840
And as historian
[INAUDIBLE] has noted,

00:26:46.840 --> 00:26:48.610
the camera obscura
can be understood

00:26:48.610 --> 00:26:50.830
not only as a
performative device, which

00:26:50.830 --> 00:26:52.900
is to say a tool
for representing

00:26:52.900 --> 00:26:56.170
an urban space, for
example, but also

00:26:56.170 --> 00:26:59.130
as an epistemological
model that articulates

00:26:59.130 --> 00:27:02.860
a relationship between an
observer and the world.

00:27:02.860 --> 00:27:06.190
Here, we find the construction
of a monocular subject

00:27:06.190 --> 00:27:09.790
isolated and ensconced within
a dark room to which the world

00:27:09.790 --> 00:27:13.200
has gathered its image
through a pinhole or oculus

00:27:13.200 --> 00:27:14.860
and projected onto
an interior wall

00:27:14.860 --> 00:27:17.650
of an observational device.

00:27:17.650 --> 00:27:22.780
Now, if we compare this device
with that of the stereoscope,

00:27:22.780 --> 00:27:26.620
a different story and a
different observing subject

00:27:26.620 --> 00:27:27.820
emerges.

00:27:27.820 --> 00:27:30.610
As a byproduct of early
19th century advances

00:27:30.610 --> 00:27:33.610
in physiological
optics, the stereoscope

00:27:33.610 --> 00:27:37.300
capitalized on the discovery
that with binocular vision,

00:27:37.300 --> 00:27:39.790
each eye sees something
slightly differently

00:27:39.790 --> 00:27:43.780
due to the angular disparity
existing between them.

00:27:43.780 --> 00:27:46.600
The production of depth
in sight was subsequently

00:27:46.600 --> 00:27:49.870
understood to be in some way
related to the mind's ability

00:27:49.870 --> 00:27:53.830
to unite and reconcile
two dissimilar images.

00:27:53.830 --> 00:27:55.660
Within this context,
the stereoscope

00:27:55.660 --> 00:27:58.290
was developed to reproduce
this optical experience

00:27:58.290 --> 00:28:00.430
mechanically.

00:28:00.430 --> 00:28:03.550
Now, significantly, the
device marks an intent

00:28:03.550 --> 00:28:06.370
not just to represent
a given space,

00:28:06.370 --> 00:28:09.500
but actually to
simulate its presence.

00:28:09.500 --> 00:28:11.770
What is sought is not
merely a likeness,

00:28:11.770 --> 00:28:14.586
but a lucid tangibility.

00:28:14.586 --> 00:28:16.210
With the stereoscope,
one is confronted

00:28:16.210 --> 00:28:20.820
not with the view of the world
through an aperture or a frame,

00:28:20.820 --> 00:28:23.660
but rather with the
technical reconstitution

00:28:23.660 --> 00:28:26.420
of an already reproduced
world fragmented

00:28:26.420 --> 00:28:28.675
into two non-identical models.

00:28:31.440 --> 00:28:35.090
Through the incorporation
of an observing subject

00:28:35.090 --> 00:28:36.930
into the mechanics
of the device,

00:28:36.930 --> 00:28:40.275
the stereoscopic image
is subsequently produced.

00:28:40.275 --> 00:28:44.070
Now, the body is immobilized and
integrated with the apparatus.

00:28:44.070 --> 00:28:45.960
The subject becomes
a participant

00:28:45.960 --> 00:28:48.120
in the production
of a verisimilitude

00:28:48.120 --> 00:28:51.840
through a process of unifying
and reconciling the experience

00:28:51.840 --> 00:28:53.260
of difference.

00:28:53.260 --> 00:28:56.260
This junk disjunction between
an experience and its cause

00:28:56.260 --> 00:29:00.750
is rarified, the real
conflated with the optical.

00:29:00.750 --> 00:29:04.450
Absent is the notion of a point
of view in a Cartesian sense

00:29:04.450 --> 00:29:08.160
as might be characterized
by the camera obscura.

00:29:08.160 --> 00:29:12.590
There is, in the end,
nothing out there.

00:29:12.590 --> 00:29:15.860
So the radical differences
between these pre-cinematic

00:29:15.860 --> 00:29:19.040
devices highlight the role of
the apparatus in constituting

00:29:19.040 --> 00:29:22.190
not only the parameters of
what we know about the world,

00:29:22.190 --> 00:29:25.130
but also how we conceive
our relationship to it,

00:29:25.130 --> 00:29:27.440
and ultimately how
we know the world

00:29:27.440 --> 00:29:31.790
and locate our agency
to act within it.

00:29:31.790 --> 00:29:35.530
Now, fast forward to late 20th
century urban observations

00:29:35.530 --> 00:29:39.730
and the work of William Whyte
and his street life project,

00:29:39.730 --> 00:29:43.360
which aimed to study how
people behave and interact

00:29:43.360 --> 00:29:46.390
within urban environments
and with urban environments

00:29:46.390 --> 00:29:48.330
through a structured
research protocol

00:29:48.330 --> 00:29:52.000
that aspired to empirical
observations, in this case,

00:29:52.000 --> 00:29:54.630
involving time
lapse photography.

00:29:54.630 --> 00:29:58.420
This is a photograph of the
apparatus in question, a Super

00:29:58.420 --> 00:30:05.390
8 film camera and a clock which
was persistently in the frame.

00:30:05.390 --> 00:30:08.250
Now, I'd like to play for you
a short excerpt from his film,

00:30:08.250 --> 00:30:10.780
The Social Life of Small
Urban Spaces, which

00:30:10.780 --> 00:30:13.510
documents the project and
distills a few observations

00:30:13.510 --> 00:30:16.130
from the results.

